Firearms training associates is a lucky company because we have been able to draft in some
of the best instructors in the world.
We have special operations guys.
We have guys from the US military, from foreign militaries that work for us.
They provide a great deal of insight into self-defense.
So we developed this so that our customers could come on the weekends and get the best
training in the world.
We pride ourselves on our civilian training.
It's our arm civilian that's one of the most important things to us.
We want to teach them how to survive dangerous situations.
When you come through the course, as long as you're performing at a acceptable level,
you're going to get a certificate that puts our stamp on it.
And we take it serious when we put our stamp on there.
When you get our gold label, that means that you pass the class that you've attended.
We have a firearm training associates, proud sponsor of Inform Descent.
Find out more at ftatv.com.
Inform Descent, the intersection of healthcare and politics.
With Dr. Jeff Markey, board certified primary care physician.
And Dr. Mark McDonald, board certified child adolescent and adult psychiatrist.
Well Mark, great to be with you on another episode of Inform Descent.
Welcome back.
Back to you.
You've been traveling and we've got some really fascinating guests to talk about.
A very disturbing but unfortunately growing topic here in America and probably around
the world.
We've got, forgive me if I pronounce your names wrong, but we've got Kat, Katason, who is
a person who is D transitioned.
We'll talk more about that.
And Stephanie Nguyen, who's a therapist and also the associate producer on an upcoming
documentary called Affirmation Generation.
Mark, you and I both were able to see part of that documentary and we'll talk a little
bit about that.
So, Kat and Stephanie, welcome to Inform Descent.
Thank you for having us.
It's great to be here.
Yeah, thank you so much.
If you're watching on the Patreon network, you'll see over Kat's left shoulder.
There's a beautiful cat.
With Kat, what's your cat's name?
This one's name is Teddy.
Another one's name is Pepper.
She might make an appearance at some point too.
Great.
I've got one named Winston that likes to hop in front of the camera as well.
So we'll see if she shows up here shortly.
So Kat, you've got quite a story and it's not unfortunately, very unfortunately, it's
not a unique story, but you've been brave enough to share your experience.
So start wherever you'd like and tell us about your experience.
Sure.
First and foremost, I'm a singer and a musician.
I grew up in a musical family and I started performing with my family at around age seven.
So that was a really big part of my life and it's just extremely important to me.
And I always wanted to do it as a career someday and just be able to have the freedom to do
that as much as I wanted.
But also, it's starting at a young age.
I struggled with what people call gender dysphoria.
I felt uncomfortable being a girl.
For various reasons, I think most of them were social reasons.
Like for instance, feeling unsafe in social settings as a girl, not having the freedom
to like I saw, I would see like little boys being able to take their shirts off in public
and stuff like that and a new like as a girl that wasn't okay for me to do and that
felt very limiting and just, you know, various other things.
I also have, you know, not to go into too much detail, but I do have a history of trauma
and abuse as well.
And I know that that affected me as well.
So at age five, I asked my mom if it was possible to become a boy and she didn't even really
know anything about transgender people at that time.
And she said, no, it's not.
And so I just kind of dumped the idea until I was 13.
And at that time, I was online and I was, I don't even remember how I stumbled across
it, but I found a forum for, quote, female to male transgender people and it had tips
on passing and binding your chest and packing and, you know, how you could access testosterone.
Thankfully, I'm a bit older than some D transitioners and so puberty blockers was not,
that wasn't something that was like all the rage back then.
Like I didn't even think it was really possible to transition until I was an adult, but pretty
much at age 13, I started planning like as soon as I get out of my parents' house, like
I'm going to transition.
And but it was, you know, it was a hard decision for me because it's like I, my singing voice
was so important to me.
And so it actually took me until I was in my mid 20s to start kind of considering the
possibility of transition again.
And when I was 28, it was when I started to finally medicalize.
Well, actually previously when I was 23, I had done one dose of testosterone, but I started
taking testosterone like continuously at 28.
I started planning to have top surgery to remove my breasts.
And I was talking with a surgeon to have that done.
And but, you know, it's kind of a good thing and a bad thing.
I started to have health, negative health effects like very quickly in my case.
Like just liver and gallbladder symptoms, heart palpitations, which was also probably
from the binding.
I started to, you know, not only was my singing voice like changing, but it became very painful.
And I started to have this throat problem that I'm still dealing with today.
And so my quality of life was just deteriorating because of the, you know, a not being able
to sing and also the physical health issues.
So I ended up detransitioning after less than a year.
I just kind of went off of the testosterone and canceled my top surgery, but it took to
like ideologically detransition.
I'd say it took like six months to a year because that's another part of it.
It's just like changing your mindset and like not believing that you're born in the wrong
body any longer.
So that's kind of my story in a nutshell.
And since then I've, you know, I've gone back to school and I graduated with my degree
in molecular biology and I've also returned to doing music.
So yeah.
So if I can ask you a few questions and please don't answer if you're not comfortable.
You make the assumption that people understand what you're talking about.
Some day I do, but I think a far larger number of people do not understand some of the language
you're using.
So you talk about things like binding, explain to the audience what you mean by that.
So there's this whole idea of, you know, the whole idea behind transgender is your, your
soul or your mind doesn't match your body.
You know, some people even say like you can have a female brain in a male body or a male
brain in a female body, which is what I thought I had.
And so, you know, it's not the brain that's wrong.
It's the body that's wrong.
And so there's certain traits that kind of identify you as the sex that you are.
In my case, you know, I grew breasts when I was around 13 and that's around the same
time that I started binding with an ACE bandage, which is actually really harmful.
I don't recommend that to anyone to do.
But so yeah, I was, I was binding.
I started with an ACE bandage and then later I bought some like commercial binders, but
I did it on and off for years and years.
It's just like tightly constricting the chest, which also constricts your breathing.
So it's, it's really not a healthy thing to do.
And people just tend to talk about it in the trans community, like it's harmless, but it's
actually pretty risky.
It's relatively timely because recently the store target has come out and announced that
they are going to actually sell supplies to transitioning folks that include items to
help them bind.
And another word you used is packing.
Explain what that is.
So that is essentially simulating a more male looking crotch area.
So some people will pack with like a sock, for instance, and then there's like commercial
packers that are supposed to actually, you know, look like you have something down there
that you don't.
And so I never went expensive with mine, but usually like a pair of socks or something.
Just the kind of, yeah, I can seal that area and make it look a little more convincing.
But I didn't really do that very often because I just had trouble passing in general, even
when I was on testosterone.
Like I'm very, very petite and small bone.
So it would have been like pretty difficult for me to pass as a man.
I would have probably had to stay on testosterone for like years.
And even then like I'm just so small that like people probably would have noticed that
I was trans.
And you went so far as to actually schedule the term that's used and I think it's used
to normalize, minimize, sterilize what's actually being done is you went so far and
scheduled top, top surgery.
Yeah.
You scheduled a procedure to actually have your female breasts removed permanently.
Mm hmm.
And then it's something that means your mind.
Yeah, pretty much like two months before I would have had it done was like when I started,
well I went through this really dramatic voice change was what kind of triggered me to start
questioning some of the like permanent changes.
Like my voice had been changing gradually and I was excited to be able to start hitting
you know some of the lower notes and like seeing some songs that were designed for men.
But then there was this one really dramatic voice change where suddenly like I not only
could I not sing but it was like painful and you know uncomfortable to speak as well.
And like so that like after that was triggered I realized that doing music was a huge like
coping mechanism for me and like emotional it was relieving to me from my distress to
be able to be creative and like saying and do music.
And so when I couldn't do that it was like I was like oh my gosh like what am I doing?
Like I don't know if I'm doing the right thing anymore.
And so I decided to like just I initially didn't think I was canceling it for good but
I was just like I'm going to hold off on getting the surgery because like I want to make sure
that it's like not going to be another change that I could regret.
So I'm really thankful that I did cancel that because that would have been a huge recovery
and just you know a lot of people I know have gone that far and even even further before
they detransitioned and it's not an easy thing to recover from.
And you mentioned earlier and Cheryl knew if you want but I'm just curious when you were
younger you had significant abuse.
Is that a commonality amongst people that want to transition?
I would say from the people I know that I have transition and detransition it's definitely
like more common than the general population especially like female detransitioners like
a lot of them went through abuse and like didn't feel safe as a woman like that is one
of the common themes.
It's not the same for everybody but that's kind of like one of the common narratives
you hear for sure.
Mark talk a little bit about your understanding with folks that are wanting to transition
or feel that they're in the wrong gendered body.
Something that Kat had brought up that I think is important for everyone to understand
is that this phenomenon of transgenderism was largely restricted to boys until recently
and the female percentages have now doubled in just a few years which shows that the effective
society is driving this and not biology.
It's an environmental contagion as opposed to an internal biological one and the sooner
that we acknowledge that the sooner we'll be able to actually help people who are suffering
because there is an emotional and mental provocation.
This is not a genetic condition.
This is not an infection.
This is not something you can treat with a procedure no more than you can treat body
dysmorphia with amputation.
And I think that as we've moved away from allowing people to harm themselves who have
a body dysmorphia by cutting off body parts, we should be if we are moral and ethical
and caring people.
We should be doing the same for people who are suffering from confusion about what their
gender identity is.
So that's something that most people are not aware of in the general community.
This is a largely a female phenomenon now and that means that we're really failing young
girls and we're sort of revictimizing many of them.
As you said, Kat, you suffered a lot of abuse when you were younger and now you and others
have been re-abused essentially by adults.
And I think that's really tragic and inexcusable.
I was curious to ask you something.
I don't think you've answered this.
Was there a moment where you realized that this was wrong, that you were heading in the
wrong direction and what provoked it?
A lot of people that are trying to help those who have been taken down this wrong path,
ask the question, what is it that can change people's minds?
What do they need to know to be able to shift?
And I'm wondering what it was for you that allowed you to realize that you were harming
yourself.
You weren't helping yourself.
So a few things.
What I said earlier about it was actually kind of fortunate that I had health issues
early on.
That was one thing because I could actually feel that I was harming my body.
I mean relatively healthy year, I'll say, because I did also struggle with an eating
disorder for a lot of years, which also did some damage to my body.
But I started having these crazy physical symptoms very quickly that I didn't have before.
It was a pronounced difference.
So I could actually feel that harm was happening to my body.
And how I sort of justified that for a while was like, well, this is the only way.
This is the only treatment for gender dysphoria.
So I guess it's better than the alternative.
But when basically when I lost my singing voice, I was just like, okay, this is it.
There has to be something better.
I wasn't ready to accept myself as a woman straight away, but I just can't keep medically
transitioning.
And my fear is that a lot of people, it's a lot later when they realize the harm.
A lot of people have to go through a surgery or they don't have side effects from the hormones
until five or 10 years down the line.
And that's what we're hearing from a lot of people or it triggers an autoimmune condition,
especially for male detransitioners or heart problems or something like that.
And so I am fortunate that it happened early for me.
Kat, didn't any of the doctors along the way, the ones that were prescribing testosterone
or the surgeon who agreed that they would remove your breast, didn't any of them talk
about this with you and suggest or want you to see a therapist or get counseling?
No, therapy was never really recommended to me because there's something called the informed
consent model of care, care, lots of air quotes in this conversation, which is usually the
case with like gender identity ideology.
But I basically just, I got my hormones through Planned Parenthood, which is what a lot of
people are doing now because they work off of the informed consent model, which means
basically you just either go in or for me, it was over the phone and they just basically
prescribe it to you if you ask it.
Like they did tell me some, you know, effects of the testosterone, but they mostly focused
on like the aesthetics.
Like they're like, okay, your voice will get deeper, you'll grow facial hair.
And like it was very little like of the actual medical side effects that could happen.
Like I remember really the only warning they gave me was like, you know, you probably shouldn't
smoke or like drink to excess when you're on this medication.
And it's like pretty much any doctor will say that.
Like it's just like a routine thing for them to say like don't smoke or like, you know,
they ask you if you smoke.
So like I didn't really, I didn't realize how serious the risks were because, you know,
despite having a background in biology, like I had taken things that trans activists said
to reassure me.
And you know, I mean, the doctors presented it to me as if it was relatively safe as well.
Kat, where are you now?
Are you in therapy?
Where are you with your own sexuality and your comfort level in your own body?
Where is Kat today?
I'd say today I'm doing pretty well, like, definitely better than I was when I was transitioning
or before that.
I think that like I have been to therapy on and off and also meditation has been a really,
really helpful tool for me.
So those things and then, you know, right now I'm just I'm working on myself still and
I'm really invested in my art and activism.
So, you know, I haven't really like my only relationship right now is kind of like with
my art, I guess I'm married to my art right now and I'm enjoying that.
But, you know, if the right opportunity comes along in the future, like I'm, you know, I'm
happy to like still have the option to have children, which not every D transitioner has
sadly.
And for a while, you know, I didn't know if this could have affected my fertility, but
then, you know, my period, thankfully did come back and everything.
So I'm really thankful for that.
And your parents?
My parents are great.
I, you know, pretty much we were somewhat estranged when I was trans because they actually did
not affirm me.
At least not not completely.
Like at one point my mom did call me my preferred name because she didn't want me to completely
like cut her off.
But this was when I was an adult, not a kid.
But yeah, they were not affirming of like the whole gender thing.
And I think if they had actually affirmed and encouraged me down this path, I probably would,
you know, feel some level of like anger or resentment.
You know, I'm sure they would have thought they were doing the right thing.
But, so now that I've like the transition, like we have a good relationship and, you
know, they just, they love me no matter if I, I mean, they love me when I was trans too,
but they're happy to see me like not harming my body anymore, for sure.
Yeah, well, you're certainly very brave and Stephanie, you are the associate producer
of an upcoming documentary called Affirmation Generation.
And of course, it describes Cat's story.
Tell us a little bit about the documentary and why did you make this?
So our film features the stories of several detransitioners, including Cat, as well as
some other female, as well as male people who've gone through this experience, various
hormones and procedures and have suffered the consequences medically and psychologically.
And more than that, they've been betrayed and abandoned by the authorities.
They put their trust in during a time of vulnerability.
And that's why I'm out here doing this type of work.
We have many hardworking people behind this film, including parents who've tried to help
their kids not fall down that path too far.
And it's just time to expose what's going on with the gender crisis.
You know, there's been a 4,000 percent increase, as you were saying, in especially adolescent
girls with rapid onset gender dysphoria.
In our film, we interview Dr. Lisa Lippman, who coined the term rapid onset gender dysphoria.
And in addition to her and detransitioners, we have doctors, therapists and professionals
in journalism and research, all coming together to explore what has happened to people like
Cat and where is this coming from?
And what do we need to do to prepare ourselves for all of the people like Cat, who are coming
down the pipeline?
And are there any lawmakers that you're working with that are trying to put forward legislation
to prevent, especially with minor children, to prevent this pathway from occurring?
Well, things are really coming to a head in the United States right now.
It's hard to keep up, even as someone who has my finger on the pulse, it's hard to keep
up because every state, you know, there's states either banning so-called gender affirming
care for youth while there's other states like mine, unfortunately, Oregon.
And you can relate, you're in California that are proposing to be these sort of sanctuary
states.
So here in Oregon, I'm working with my representatives.
We've tragically had House Bill 2002 go through, which is pretty disastrous because
it takes away parental rights for parents to even know if their kids are getting, whether
it's abortions or so-called sex change operations.
But things are coming to a head and I hear that we're going to be facing this at a national
level.
There are many great organizations doing wonderful work.
Like one that I know of is Do No Harm.
There's a Society for Evidence-Based Gender Medicine and Partners for Ethical Care.
And then Kat is also newly working with an organization called Transition Justice.
Did you want to speak to that, Kat?
Yes.
Thanks for bringing that up.
So Transition Justice is a nonprofit that's connecting, we say, survivors of experimental
gender medicine with legal assistance.
And we have, we know of about 12 active cases right now and nine of which we facilitated.
So I've been mostly managing the social media for Transition Justice and it's also
great to spread awareness because like, you know, there's a lot of the public that still
doesn't know what's happening.
And I think the reason why this has gone so far, part of the reason is that a lot of
it's happening behind closed doors.
So being able to get the word out on social media, like that's been really powerful, I
think.
So I'm really grateful to be working with this organization.
Kat, what's your message to parents?
What should parents do if they have a child that is interested in transitioning?
Yeah, that's a tough one because, you know, obviously I've been on the kid side of it,
you know, being a trans kid and like, but I would say get in touch with some groups who
can help you.
Our duty is a good one.
They're a parents group that is dedicated to protecting children from gender ideology.
But also I would say like definitely show your kid understanding and compassion and like,
you know, hold space for them and just ask, ask like non-judgmental questions, you know,
and like really listen to them, but don't affirm the identity because that is just, you
know, it all begins with the social transition and like the gender affirmation.
Like that's where it all starts.
And a lot of these kids end up permanently medicalizing because they were affirmed at
every step along along the way by their friends and by their parents.
It seems as if schools revere kids that want to transition or be something different than
their biological sex.
Do you think that's part of the problem is that there's this culture of celebrating those
that want to transition?
I do think it could be part of the problem these days.
Like I said, I'm an older, I'm a millennial, not Gen Z. And so like when I was in school,
it wasn't quite at that point where it was so much of a social contagion.
Like if at my school, if you were trans, you were definitely an oddball.
Like, you know, I was like one of the only trans people that I knew.
I think I met one other trans person in high school.
So it wasn't like this really common thing back then.
But I do think that nowadays, yeah, it's a way to be special.
I feel like, I mean, who really wants to be a boring cis kid when it's like you could
be trans or non-binary and you could be part of this whole community.
So I do think that that's part of the appeal for some kids.
Yeah, Mark, what about that?
Like the popular culture now, you're celebrated if you're different.
You're celebrated if you want to be something that you're not.
And if you're just a boring cis kid, you're looked down upon.
One of the big problems that I see with the growing firestorm of this transgender movement
is that it thrives on the natural and expected developmental challenges and stress of young girls.
Your goal as an adolescent girl is to become a woman.
It's to create an identity.
And that's not easy.
Everyone struggles with that.
And rather than help young girls in guiding them towards becoming women,
the throwaway solution is now, well, don't bother becoming a woman.
And just change your sex as if that's even possible when it's not.
It's a fantasy.
But it's an avoidant behavior.
And young children and adolescent girls will take what's easier, most humans will.
And of course, that takes them down the path that Kath took, which luckily,
you were able to avoid before you went off the cliff, but many of them don't.
And they wind up becoming infertile with osteoporosis and horrible multi-organ system problems
and elevated risk of cancers.
It's really, really tragic not to mention the emotional and mental suffering.
The documentary, Stephanie, that you produced, I think is one of the three most important arms
in the battle to fight this movement, the other two being financial and political.
We talked about the politics.
We haven't mentioned the financial.
I know there's a lot of lawsuits being filed, particularly against Kaiser, for mutilating young women.
And I think that this is the moment we see multi-hundred million dollar lawsuits with
with juries, which is going to happen eventually, whether it happens this year or in five years.
We're going to see a deluge of this.
That's going to shut it down very quickly because the people who are performing these surgeries
are making a lot of money off of it.
That's why there was such a big push to shut down the legislation in Florida
that Governor DeSantis proposed and passed to ban taxpayer funded
sponsorship of these surgeries once you cut off the money flow, then the beast dies.
But the third arm is education.
It's the social culture.
And this is where I think we haven't really made a lot of headway yet.
As Jeff said earlier, most people don't know what these terms are, binding and packing and
top surgeries.
Many Americans aren't aware of it.
Stephanie, how important do you think it is for documentaries like yours to get out there,
to educate just everyday Americans, parents and young people about what's actually happening,
to get the truth out so that people can actually make informed decisions?
Well, I think it's important that we spread the message for a number of reasons.
Of course, many desperate, caring parents want to stop their kids from going down that path in
the first place. But moreover, we need to prepare for more people who have had these experiences.
And they've been traumatized by the very people who are supposed to help them.
Doctors, therapists, when you asked Kat if she had a therapist and Kat is in that category of
people who went through the so-called informed consent process, so she didn't have a therapist
involved in her process. But there are a lot of people for whom therapists played a role
in pushing them down this path. Therapists were the ones who affirmed their gender dysphoria,
who colluded with their mental health issues.
And Stephanie, you are a therapist in case the listeners have not caught on yet.
You're going up against your own people. So I want to point that out that this takes a lot of
courage to call out people in your profession who are harming their own patients.
So when it comes to the education component, my main message for the mental health community
is look how badly we have failed this whole community of people. You're giving them what they want now.
You know, to these woke therapists who are virtue signaling, who are affirming the gender
identities of their patients, feeling so good about themselves. You feel good about yourself now.
You feel like you're doing the right thing. You feel like your patients appreciate you.
But do you know where that person's going to end up five or 10 years down the line
when they are suffering mentally and physically and they're more suicidal than they've ever been
in their life and they hate your guts as a therapist. A lot of therapists don't want to face the reality
that there are homicidal levels of rage in people who feel that they have been damaged by this.
So the education component needs to be about the unique nature of the trauma that people have
been through, the unique medical situations, the unprecedented, frankly, medical situations that
people who would otherwise be fairly healthy because they're young are finding themselves in
in their 20s and 30s. And then the mental health community needs to do a complete 180 to figure out
how are we going to reach out and build bridges and establish trust because we certainly can't
count on people who've been through these experiences, especially when therapists had a role in it to
turn towards us for help. So there needs to be a whole new level of trauma informed care.
You also asked earlier, you asked Kat what parents can do. And I was sort of chuckling at
all the questions you asked Kat because they're the questions I hear D transitioners being asked
so much of the time. And I just want to take a moment to appreciate Kat and the other
T transitioners who do do things like join our pod, our excuse me, our documentary or come on my
podcast and talk about that their experiences because it takes a lot of strength to do that.
It takes a lot of strength to tell your trauma stories over and over and to try to give advice
to other people when you're still in your own healing process. So another education component
needs to be for the parents. And that's where I do my parent consulting, parent therapy. We also
have, you know, one of the other therapists in our documentary, Sasha Ayad has a whole parent
coaching system as well because we need to help the adults who care the most about these young
people who are frankly in a cult. And it takes a whole new level of psychological intervention
to get them out of that. Stephanie, where will people be able to see the documentary and where
will be when will it be released? Sure. So we previously gave an early access to an early
edition of our film. And now we are getting our ducks in a row because we've partnered with a
global distribution firm. So as of June 20th, that will be live. So I can't tell you exactly
everywhere, but it will be view on demand worldwide. And you can stay tuned by visiting our website
and following us on social media. So our website is affirmationgenerationmovie.com. You can follow
us on Twitter at 2022, 2022, Affirmation, or on Instagram at affirmationgeneration. And we'll
be posting updates as things come along with our distribution efforts as to where exactly you'll
be able to watch that film. And then I'm also excited to announce we just got word that it's
looking like June 21st, there are going to be actual theater showings through AMC theaters.
That's wonderful. That's amazing. That is awesome. AMC agreed to show the movie. That's unbelievable.
And it's what's in my inbox right now. I don't like. You guys have a formal premiere or something
of that sort would love to would love to come along and support you and Kat. And Kat, I just want to
tell you that I think you're incredibly brave. And I'm sure this continues to be a struggle for you.
I'm a primary care doc. Mark is a psychiatrist. There's anything that either of us can do to help
support you. Please reach out. You've got Beth and Doc's contact information. And I'd be happy to
support you and help you anyway. And Stephanie, thank you for bringing this movie forward. I
think it's important information that more people need to be aware of, especially parents
and young kids that are in school and seeing this happen live action. I think it's a critically
important movie. And I applaud you for bringing this forward. And Kat, thank you for your bravery
and your courage in speaking out. Thank you for having us. Thank you. You've been listening to
informed dissent with Dr. Jeff Markey, board certified primary care physician, and Dr. Mark
McDonald, board certified child adolescent and adult psychiatrist.
Informed dissent, the intersection of health care and politics.
